//! Server-to-client Huffman compression.
//!
//! # A fixed tree, not a computed one
//!
//! This is not Huffman as a compression algorithm — nothing here counts symbol
//! frequencies or builds a tree. The client has one table baked into its binary
//! and no way to learn another, so the server must use the identical table or
//! the client decodes noise. It is really a fixed prefix code that happens to
//! have been generated by Huffman's algorithm, once, in 1997.
//!
//! That means the table is not tunable and not improvable. It is a constant of
//! the protocol, like a packet id.
//!
//! # What is compressed
//!
//! Server-to-client packets only, and only after the login handshake. The
//! client never compresses anything it sends, so there is no decompressor here
//! — only the encoder in [`compress`]. [`decompress`] exists to test the
//! encoder against, and to read packet captures.
//!
//! Ported from SphereServer's `common/crypto/CHuffman.cpp`.

/// Number of entries: 256 byte values plus the terminator.
const TREE_SIZE: usize = 257;

/// Index of the end-of-stream symbol.
const TERMINAL: usize = 256;

/// The client's baked-in code table.
///
/// Each entry packs a code and its bit length into a `u16`: the low four bits
/// are the length, the remaining twelve are the code, most significant bit
/// first. Entry 256 is the terminator every compressed stream ends with.
///
/// Sphere calls this "the golden key for (0.0.0.0)" and notes the addresses it
/// was lifted from in the 2.0.3 and 2.0.4 client binaries. Do not touch it.
#[rustfmt::skip]
